# MCP Server TypeScript Starter

A minimal, complete Model Context Protocol server in TypeScript that actually meets the quality bar.

## What makes this different

Most MCP server templates work for the happy path and fall over the moment anything goes wrong. This one ships with the 8 things those templates forget:

1. Graceful shutdown (SIGTERM/SIGINT)
2. Input validation with clear errors
3. Error messages that teach the LLM how to fix the call
4. Stderr-only logging (stdout is the JSON-RPC channel)
5. Typed tool schemas
6. Concurrency-safe handlers
7. Declared scope (project root only by default)
8. A test harness that actually exercises the protocol

## Project layout

```
my-mcp/
  src/
    index.ts            # server setup + transport
    tools/
      echo.ts           # example tool
      read-project.ts   # example tool with scoped file access
    auth.ts             # reads MY_MCP_TOKEN env var (no hardcoded secrets)
    log.ts              # stderr-only logger
  test/
    protocol.test.ts    # tests against a real stdio client
  package.json
  tsconfig.json
  README.md             # declares scope, auth, capabilities
```

## src/index.ts

```ts
import { Server } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js';
import { StdioServerTransport } from '@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js';
import { echoTool } from './tools/echo.js';
import { readProjectTool } from './tools/read-project.js';
import { log } from './log.js';

const server = new Server(
  { name: 'my-mcp', version: '1.0.0' },
  { capabilities: { tools: {} } },
);

const tools = [echoTool, readProjectTool];

server.setRequestHandler('tools/list', async () => ({
  tools: tools.map(t => ({
    name: t.name,
    description: t.description,
    inputSchema: t.inputSchema,
  })),
}));

server.setRequestHandler('tools/call', async (req) => {
  const tool = tools.find(t => t.name === req.params.name);
  if (!tool) {
    return {
      isError: true,
      content: [{ type: 'text', text: `Unknown tool: ${req.params.name}. Available: ${tools.map(t => t.name).join(', ')}` }],
    };
  }
  try {
    return await tool.handler(req.params.arguments ?? {});
  } catch (err) {
    log.error(`tool ${tool.name} failed: ${err}`);
    return {
      isError: true,
      content: [{ type: 'text', text: err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err) }],
    };
  }
});

const transport = new StdioServerTransport();
await server.connect(transport);
log.info('my-mcp started');

// Graceful shutdown — critical for not leaving zombies
for (const sig of ['SIGTERM', 'SIGINT'] as const) {
  process.on(sig, async () => {
    log.info(`received ${sig}, shutting down`);
    await server.close();
    process.exit(0);
  });
}
```

## src/tools/echo.ts

```ts
export const echoTool = {
  name: 'echo',
  description: 'Echo the input back. Useful for sanity-checking the MCP connection.',
  inputSchema: {
    type: 'object',
    properties: {
      message: { type: 'string', description: 'Message to echo back' },
    },
    required: ['message'],
  },
  async handler(args: unknown): Promise<{ content: Array<{ type: 'text'; text: string }> }> {
    const { message } = args as { message?: unknown };
    if (typeof message !== 'string') {
      throw new Error("'message' must be a string");
    }
    return { content: [{ type: 'text', text: message }] };
  },
};
```

## src/tools/read-project.ts

```ts
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises';
import { resolve, relative } from 'node:path';

const PROJECT_ROOT = process.cwd();

export const readProjectTool = {
  name: 'read_project_file',
  description: 'Read a file from the project root. Path must be relative and cannot escape the project root.',
  inputSchema: {
    type: 'object',
    properties: {
      path: { type: 'string', description: 'Relative path from project root (e.g. "src/index.ts")' },
    },
    required: ['path'],
  },
  async handler(args: unknown) {
    const { path } = args as { path?: unknown };
    if (typeof path !== 'string') {
      throw new Error("'path' must be a string");
    }

    const full = resolve(PROJECT_ROOT, path);
    const rel = relative(PROJECT_ROOT, full);
    if (rel.startsWith('..') || rel.startsWith('/') || rel.startsWith('\\\\')) {
      throw new Error(`path escapes project root: ${path}`);
    }

    try {
      const content = await readFile(full, 'utf-8');
      return { content: [{ type: 'text', text: content }] };
    } catch (err) {
      const code = (err as NodeJS.ErrnoException).code;
      if (code === 'ENOENT') {
        throw new Error(`file not found: ${path}`);
      }
      if (code === 'EACCES') {
        throw new Error(`permission denied: ${path}`);
      }
      throw err;
    }
  },
};
```

Note the error messages — each tells the LLM exactly what went wrong and, where possible, how to fix it.

## src/log.ts

```ts
// Logging MUST go to stderr. stdout is reserved for JSON-RPC messages.
// If you log to stdout you will corrupt the protocol and crash the client.
export const log = {
  info: (msg: string) => process.stderr.write(`[INFO] ${new Date().toISOString()} ${msg}\n`),
  error: (msg: string) => process.stderr.write(`[ERROR] ${new Date().toISOString()} ${msg}\n`),
  debug: (msg: string) => {
    if (process.env.MCP_DEBUG === '1') {
      process.stderr.write(`[DEBUG] ${new Date().toISOString()} ${msg}\n`);
    }
  },
};
```

## Install and run

```bash
npm install @modelcontextprotocol/sdk
npx tsc
node dist/index.js
```

## Wire it into Claude Code

Create `.mcp.json` in your project root:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "my-mcp": {
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["./path/to/dist/index.js"]
    }
  }
}
```

Restart Claude Code. Test with: `claude --mcp-debug` and ask the agent to use your `echo` tool.

## What this template does NOT do (on purpose)

- No HTTP transport — stdio only. HTTP transport is a legitimate option for hosted servers, but it has its own security surface. Start with stdio.
- No auto-reload — you restart the server manually during dev.
- No hardcoded secrets — always read from `process.env`.
- No `eval()` or arbitrary script execution. That's a different, much more dangerous class of server.

